<textList name="TIPS_LIST">
	<text>TIP: The civil war has set fathers against sons and best friends against each other - but the loyalists will show no mercy.</text>
	<text>TIP: Weapons - Race-specific weapons are rarer, more expensive, and deadlier than their generic counterparts.</text>
	<text>TIP: Weapon types - Missiles are good at ignoring shields, lasers fire damaging beams which shields stop, and kinetic weapons are somewhere in the middle.</text>
	<text>TIP: Pausing -  Press SPACE at any time to pause the game. You can still issue orders to crew or manipulate system power while paused.</text>
	<text>TIP: Upgrading - Weapons are deadlier in Sonata, and many ignore shields. Upgrade your ship's defense as soon as possible.</text>
	<text>TIP: Weapon types - The United Empire uses kinetic weapons like railguns and Gauss guns. Drivers fire more quickly; Empire weapons tend to breach and ignore one shield.</text>
	<text>TIP: Weapon types - The Sower use big cannon and quick-firing autocannon; some require ammunition. Their ships were built by the Endless, but their weapons are more primitive.</text>
	<text>TIP: Weapon types - Sophons wield lasers, incredibly deadly weapons that cause fires and damage multiple rooms. Make sure your opponent's shields are down before firing.</text>
	<text>TIP: System Damage -  When a System fully breaks due to fire or boarders, the hull also takes one damage.</text>
	<text>TIP: United Empire - Most humans are citizens. It is democratic and has liberal laws. Humans being human, the United Empire can be quite aggressive towards other species.</text>
	<text>TIP: The Sower - The Endless built the Sower as intelligent terraformers. They have evolved, but retain thier mission: prepare the universe for the return of their creators.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sophons - The Sophon are an intelligent, inquisitive, emotional race. Although they are driven researchers, their interests extend to art and more...prurient activities.</text>
	<text>TIP: The Endless - Artifacts of an incredibly advanced, ancient race called the Endless have been found throughout the galaxy; they are believed to be extinct.</text>
	<text>TIP: Civil war - Many humans, unsatisfied with Empire government and society, have seceded. They are in a desparate fight for survival.</text>
	<text>TIP: Pilgrims - Most of the seceding humans are Pilgrims. Pilgrims are unique among humanity in that they view the Endless as the Gods of old - most UE citizens are secular.</text>
	<text>TIP: Shields - Modern starships are equipped with a suite of defensive measures that include armor, soft and hard anti-missile systems, and energy shields.</text>
	<text>TIP: Shield Piercing - Missiles are agile enough to avoid being shot down and too heavy to be stopped by energy shields. Remember that Defense Drones can shoot down missiles!</text>
	<text>TIP: Fire - As in ancient navies, fire is a starship's worst enemy. Many warships are built to allow atmosphere venting to prevent infernos.</text>
	<text>TIP: Breach - Ship hulls are incredibly tough, and some are made from self-repairing nanomaterial. However, you can still to blow a hole large enough to require manual repair.</text>
	<text>TIP: Evasion -  Evading enemy shots is crucial, but it requires working engines AND a pilot. Assigning an expert to man the engines will increase your evasion as well.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sensors - If the ship goes dark, you need not panic. Just fix the Sensors Subsystem. Be forewarned that in the icy blackness of space, panic may well be appropriate.</text>
	<text>TIP: Survival - I hope you know where your fucking towel is at.</text>
	<text>TIP: Lasers - Laser weapons do damage based on the number of rooms they hit. Each Shield will block 1 damage of a laser; it's best to use lasers when enemy shields are down.</text>
	<text>TIP: Health -  Pay attention to your crew's health! Use the medbay to keep them patched up.</text>
	<text>TIP: Upgrades - Don't forget to upgrade your ship!  Often shields are the highest priority, but don't underestimate the usefulness of subsystems.</text>
	<text>TIP: Fuel - Every jump consumes one unit of fuel, so keep an eye on your reserves.  Buy fuel at stores to avoid being left stranded.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sower-Human relations - Sower are peaceful unless provoked, but several times their attempts to terraform populated worlds have provoked bloody battles.</text>
	<text>TIP: Asteroids - Fighting in asteroid fields is dangerous, but use it to your advantage. Take out enemy shields and let the rocks take care of the rest.</text>
	<text>TIP: Nebulas -  Passing through a Nebula will allow you to temporarily slow down the fleet advancement but they contain their own unique dangers.</text>
	<text>TIP: Solar Flares - Solar flares will cause hull damage in addition to starting fires. Make sure your shields are up to help mitigate this effect.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sower-Sophon relations - It is safe to assume that the Sophon drive to research and understand has extended to studying the Sower; conflict between the two races is rare.</text>
	<text>TIP: Hotkeys -  You can charge or arm weapons using number hotkeys:  The Weapon Slots are 1-4 on your keyboard, and the Drones are 5-7.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sophon-Human relations - The Sophon were the first friendly race contacted by humanity; theirs is a "special relationship" characterized by curiousity and friendship.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sophon-Human relations - In the literal sense, Sophon-Human relations aren't rare. Interbreeding is impossible, but that hasn't stopped couples from enjoying the attempt.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sophon-Empire relations - The United Empire has always maintained excellent relations with the Suphon, and refrained from expanding into traditional Sophon space.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sophon-Empire relations - There are far more Humans than Sophon, and they have more of a taste for war. War between the two species is unthinkable to most, however.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sophon-Pilgrim relations - Most Sophon strongly believe in freedom and independence, and hence support peaceful secession even if they disagree with some Pilgrim ideals.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sophon-Pilgrim relations - It is well known that the Sophon disapprove of the Empire's violent handling of the secession incident.</text>
	<text>TIP: Sophon-Pilgrim relations - Sophon-Empire relations make open support for the Pilgrims diplomatically unteneble - but they do provide some help behind the scenes.</text>
	<text>TIP: Loyalists - Many loyal Empire citizens view the seceding Pilgrims as traitors. Humanity is the only known race that does not present a united front.</text>
	<text>TIP: Civil war - The United Empire legislature hastily declared war when planets seceded. The official position is that it is not a war but an internal police action.</text>
	<text>TIP: Civil war - The United Empire retained most of its industrial capacity post-secession. It will eventually win any war against the Pilgrims - if it has the stomach for it.</text>
	<text>TIP: Civil war - The Pilgrims are frantically seeking a diplimatic resolution, but the United Empire will not accept anything other than a return to the pre-war status quo.</text>
	<text>TIP: Breaches -  If a room with a breach has no Oxygen, try opening all the doors surrounding it to make it less hazardous.</text>
	<text>TIP: Dust - The galaxy is covered in this stuff. It is an intelligent nanomaterial useful for science, repair, medicine, and even currency.</text>
	<text>TIP: Dust - Dust was created by the Endless. Current technology cannot create it, but it is extremely useful in every field.</text>
	<text>TIP: Dust - All known spacefaring races have discovered the existence of Dust. Its properties are so advanced as to be indestinguishable from magic.</text>
	<text>TIP: Dust - Dust is normally detected and interacted with via specialized instruments: amber spyglasses and golden compasses. Just a gram of Dust is worth a fortune.</text>
	<text>TIP: Dust - Almost all advanced equipment makes use of Dust in its construction. Dust is near-indestructible and can be recovered after the equipment is destroyed.</text>
	<text>TIP: Font Size -  Pressing +/- will increase and decrease the font size of event texts.</text>
	<text>TIP: Weapon Order - Rearrange a weapon or drone schematic by dragging it into the desired position. The left-most slot will be the last to power down if the system is damaged.</text>
	<text>TIP: Door Subsystem - Upgrading your doors will greatly reduce the chance fire will spread between rooms and slow boarder movement.</text>
</textList>

<textList name="TIPS_LIST_PC">
	<text load="TIPS_LIST"/>
	<text>TIP: Pausing -  Press SPACE at any time to pause the game. You can still issue orders to crew or manipulate system power while paused.</text>
	<text>TIP: Selling -  Weapons, USVs, and Augments can be sold for 1/2 the purchasing price at stores. Click on the SELL tab at the top.</text>
	<text>TIP: Hotkeys -  You can charge or arm weapons using number hotkeys: The Weapon Slots are 1-4 on your keyboard, and the USVs are 5-7 (customizeable in the options).</text>
	<text>TIP: Font Size -  Pressing +/- (customizable in options) will let you change the event text size.</text>
	<text>TIP: Weapon Order -  Rearrange a Weapon or USV schematic by dragging it into the desired position. The left-most slot will be the last to power down if the system is damaged.</text>
</textList>

